{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Integrating an LLM into an IDE requires more than calling a completion API on every keystroke. The challenge is latency: a code completion that arrives two seconds after the user pauses is ignored. Building a genuinely useful IDE integration means understanding the Language Server Protocol, debouncing and cancellation, FIM prompt construction, streaming, and the UX conventions that let developers accept suggestions without breaking their flow."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "IDE integration architecture: editor sends LSP textDocument/completion RPC to LSP extension plugin, which builds FIM prompt with RAG context retrieved from codebase index, sends to LLM backend for streaming response, then returns CompletionItem list back to editor as ghost text."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Language Server Protocol"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "VS Code, Neovim, JetBrains IDEs, and Emacs all support the Language Server Protocol (LSP). LSP separates editor UI from language intelligence: the editor sends JSON-RPC messages over stdin/stdout (or a socket), and a language server responds with completions, diagnostics, hover info, and go-to-definition results. An LLM-backed completion plugin is implemented as an LSP server that intercepts "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "textDocument/completion"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " requests and replaces (or augments) the traditional static analysis results with LLM-generated suggestions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The key LSP types for completion are:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// LSP CompletionParams — what the editor sends\ninterface CompletionParams {\n  textDocument: { uri: string };   // file URI\n  position: { line: number; character: number };  // 0-indexed cursor\n  context?: {\n    triggerKind: 1 | 2 | 3;  // 1=Invoked, 2=TriggerChar, 3=Re-trigger\n    triggerCharacter?: string;\n  };\n}\n\n// LSP CompletionItem — what you return\ninterface CompletionItem {\n  label: string;           // shown in dropdown\n  insertText: string;      // text inserted on accept\n  insertTextFormat?: 1 | 2; // 1=PlainText, 2=Snippet\n  detail?: string;         // secondary label (model name, token count)\n  documentation?: string | MarkupContent;  // shown on hover\n  kind?: CompletionItemKind;  // 1=Text, 15=Snippet\n  sortText?: string;       // controls order in dropdown\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Minimal LSP Server in Python"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "pygls"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " library handles LSP JSON-RPC plumbing so you can focus on the completion logic. Here is a minimal server that registers a completion handler and delegates to an LLM:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from pygls.server import LanguageServer\nfrom lsprotocol.types import (\n    TEXT_DOCUMENT_COMPLETION,\n    CompletionItem,\n    CompletionItemKind,\n    CompletionList,\n    CompletionParams,\n)\nimport asyncio\n\nserver = LanguageServer(\"llm-complete\", \"v0.1\")\n\n@server.feature(TEXT_DOCUMENT_COMPLETION)\nasync def completions(ls: LanguageServer, params: CompletionParams):\n    doc = ls.workspace.get_text_document(params.textDocument.uri)\n    lines = doc.source.splitlines(keepends=True)\n\n    # Split at cursor\n    line_idx = params.position.line\n    char_idx = params.position.character\n    prefix_lines = lines[:line_idx] + [lines[line_idx][:char_idx]] if line_idx < len(lines) else lines\n    suffix_lines = [lines[line_idx][char_idx:]] + lines[line_idx + 1:] if line_idx < len(lines) else []\n\n    prefix = \"\".join(prefix_lines)\n    suffix = \"\".join(suffix_lines)\n    language = doc.uri.rsplit(\".\", 1)[-1] if \".\" in doc.uri else \"text\"\n\n    completion_text = await generate_fim_completion(prefix, suffix, language)\n    if not completion_text:\n        return CompletionList(is_incomplete=False, items=[])\n\n    item = CompletionItem(\n        label=\"✦ \" + completion_text[:40].replace(\"\\n\", \"↵\") + (\"…\" if len(completion_text) > 40 else \"\"),\n        insert_text=completion_text,\n        kind=CompletionItemKind.Snippet,\n        detail=\"LLM suggestion\",\n        sort_text=\"0\",  # float to top\n    )\n    return CompletionList(is_incomplete=False, items=[item])\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    server.start_io()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Debouncing and Cancellation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Firing an LLM request on every keystroke is wasteful and creates a backlog of in-flight requests. Two mechanisms prevent this:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Debounce"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — wait until the user has paused for 150–300 ms before sending a request. If they type again during the wait, reset the timer."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Cancellation"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if the cursor moves or a new request arrives while the previous one is in-flight, cancel it with an "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "AbortController"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (TypeScript) or "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "asyncio.CancelledError"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (Python). The LLM server must honor the abort and stop generation to avoid burning GPU time on a stale request."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// TypeScript plugin-side debounce + cancellation\nlet debounceTimer: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout> | null = null;\nlet activeController: AbortController | null = null;\n\nexport function onDidChangeTextDocument(event: vscode.TextDocumentChangeEvent) {\n  if (debounceTimer) clearTimeout(debounceTimer);\n  if (activeController) {\n    activeController.abort();      // cancel in-flight request\n    activeController = null;\n  }\n\n  debounceTimer = setTimeout(async () => {\n    activeController = new AbortController();\n    try {\n      const suggestion = await fetchCompletion(\n        event.document,\n        vscode.window.activeTextEditor!.selection.active,\n        activeController.signal,\n      );\n      if (suggestion && !activeController.signal.aborted) {\n        showGhostText(suggestion);\n      }\n    } catch (e) {\n      if ((e as Error).name !== \"AbortError\") throw e;\n    } finally {\n      activeController = null;\n    }\n  }, 200);  // 200 ms debounce\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ghost-Text UX"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ghost text is the greyed-out inline preview of the suggestion that appears to the right of the cursor without modifying the document. VS Code exposes this via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "vscode.window.createTextEditorDecorationType"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " with an "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "after"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " pseudo-element, or via the newer "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "vscode.InlineCompletionItemProvider"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " API which handles rendering automatically:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import * as vscode from \"vscode\";\n\nexport class LLMInlineProvider implements vscode.InlineCompletionItemProvider {\n  async provideInlineCompletionItems(\n    document: vscode.TextDocument,\n    position: vscode.Position,\n    context: vscode.InlineCompletionContext,\n    token: vscode.CancellationToken,\n  ): Promise<vscode.InlineCompletionList | null> {\n    const prefix = document.getText(\n      new vscode.Range(new vscode.Position(0, 0), position),\n    );\n    const suffix = document.getText(\n      new vscode.Range(position, new vscode.Position(document.lineCount, 0)),\n    );\n\n    const suggestion = await fetchFimCompletion(prefix, suffix, {\n      signal: token as unknown as AbortSignal,  // VS Code token → abort\n    });\n    if (!suggestion || token.isCancellationRequested) return null;\n\n    return {\n      items: [\n        new vscode.InlineCompletionItem(\n          suggestion,\n          new vscode.Range(position, position),\n        ),\n      ],\n    };\n  }\n}\n\n// Register in your extension's activate()\nexport function activate(ctx: vscode.ExtensionContext) {\n  ctx.subscriptions.push(\n    vscode.languages.registerInlineCompletionItemProvider(\n      { pattern: \"**\" },  // all files\n      new LLMInlineProvider(),\n    ),\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "With "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "InlineCompletionItemProvider"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", VS Code automatically handles Tab-to-accept, Escape-to-dismiss, and word-by-word acceptance with the right arrow key. You do not need to implement these key bindings yourself."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Streaming for Perceived Latency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Even if the full completion takes 1.5 seconds, showing the first five tokens in 200 ms makes the integration feel fast. Stream the response and update the ghost text incrementally as tokens arrive:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import httpx\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def stream_fim_completion(\n    prefix: str,\n    suffix: str,\n    model_url: str = \"http://localhost:8000/v1/completions\",\n    max_tokens: int = 128,\n) -> asyncio.Queue:\n    \"\"\"Returns a queue; caller reads tokens until None (sentinel).\"\"\"\n    queue: asyncio.Queue[str | None] = asyncio.Queue()\n    prompt = f\"<fim_prefix>{prefix}<fim_suffix>{suffix}<fim_middle>\"\n\n    async def _stream():\n        try:\n            async with httpx.AsyncClient(timeout=10.0) as client:\n                async with client.stream(\n                    \"POST\",\n                    model_url,\n                    json={\"model\": \"starcoder2\", \"prompt\": prompt,\n                          \"max_tokens\": max_tokens, \"stream\": True,\n                          \"stop\": [\"<|endoftext|>\", \"\\n\\n\"]},\n                ) as resp:\n                    async for line in resp.aiter_lines():\n                        if line.startswith(\"data: \") and line != \"data: [DONE]\":\n                            import json\n                            data = json.loads(line[6:])\n                            token = data[\"choices\"][0].get(\"text\", \"\")\n                            if token:\n                                await queue.put(token)\n        finally:\n            await queue.put(None)  # sentinel\n\n    asyncio.create_task(_stream())\n    return queue\n\nasync def build_completion_streaming(prefix: str, suffix: str) -> str:\n    queue = await stream_fim_completion(prefix, suffix)\n    tokens: list[str] = []\n    while True:\n        token = await asyncio.wait_for(queue.get(), timeout=5.0)\n        if token is None:\n            break\n        tokens.append(token)\n        # In a real plugin, push each token to the ghost-text renderer here\n    return \"\".join(tokens)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tracking Acceptance Rate"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Acceptance rate is the primary quality signal for an IDE integration. A low rate means suggestions are arriving too slowly, are syntactically wrong, or do not match the codebase's style. Instrument every completion event with three outcomes:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "shown"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the ghost text was rendered to the user"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "accepted"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the user pressed Tab; record "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "chars_accepted"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " and "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "chars_suggested"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "edited_after_accept"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — the user accepted but then modified the inserted text within the next 10 seconds (suggests the suggestion was partially correct)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom collections import deque\n\n@dataclass\nclass CompletionEvent:\n    request_id: str\n    language: str\n    model: str\n    chars_suggested: int\n    latency_ms: float\n    outcome: str   # \"shown\" | \"accepted\" | \"dismissed\" | \"cancelled\"\n    chars_accepted: int = 0\n\nclass AcceptanceTracker:\n    def __init__(self, window: int = 1000):\n        self._events: deque[CompletionEvent] = deque(maxlen=window)\n\n    def record(self, event: CompletionEvent) -> None:\n        self._events.append(event)\n\n    def acceptance_rate(self) -> float:\n        shown = [e for e in self._events if e.outcome in (\"shown\", \"accepted\", \"dismissed\")]\n        if not shown:\n            return 0.0\n        accepted = [e for e in shown if e.outcome == \"accepted\"]\n        return len(accepted) / len(shown)\n\n    def char_acceptance_rate(self) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Fraction of suggested characters that were actually kept.\"\"\"\n        total_suggested = sum(e.chars_suggested for e in self._events if e.outcome == \"accepted\")\n        total_kept = sum(e.chars_accepted for e in self._events if e.outcome == \"accepted\")\n        return total_kept / total_suggested if total_suggested else 0.0\n\n    def p95_latency_ms(self) -> float:\n        latencies = sorted(e.latency_ms for e in self._events)\n        if not latencies:\n            return 0.0\n        idx = int(len(latencies) * 0.95)\n        return latencies[min(idx, len(latencies) - 1)]"
          }
        ]
      },
